festival.introText: Regarded by many as the ‘Christmas Day’ of the independent creative scene, the festival will be back to bring colour, imagination and the best in new music and art to the pubs, bars, squares, studios, warehouses and ‘everywhere in between’ spaces of Chapel Street, Salford.

reviewsDisplayFour.title: Review of Sounds From the Other City 2022
reviewsDisplayFour.body: A unique festival of music and art spread across various interesting venues, in a great City. Gets better every year. The organisers should pat themselves on the back for doing such an amazing job. Also the volunteers were outstanding, friendly and helpful. Can't wait for next year's!

reviewsDisplayFour.title: Review of Sounds From the Other City - Quindecennial
reviewsDisplayFour.body:
An incredible atmosphere. Everyone was in a great mood and it had such a good feel about it. Myself and my friends really enjoyed that it was all on one location this year. A lot less FOMO. You were always where the party was at. Although the variety in previous years has been very exciting. It was nice to have a change.  The japes in the toilet queue and the L'uber trolley was very funny. Really enjoyed the food stands. Delicious and good choices for vegetarians. I took my 6 month baby and got a such a welcoming reception from the staff on the gate and around the festival . 
Just brilliant! Thank you x
reviewsDisplayFour.eventName: Sounds From the Other City - Quindecennial

news.title: Sounds From The Other City announce first wave of acts for 2023

news.title: Sounds From The Other City announces full lineup and late night after parties
news.summary: Edinburgh-born singer-songwriter, Hamish Hawk, Dutch indie quartet, Pip Blom, and Manchester favourites, Lovescene are just some of the many names recently added to the festivals already impressive lineup
